8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 522, L.D. 1292, “An Act to Codify the
10 Maine Turnpike Authority's Contributions to the Highway Fund with Regard to the
11 Sensible Transportation Policy Act”
12 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
13 'Resolve, to Establish a Working Group to Create a Plan to Integrate the Maine
14 Turnpike Authority Within the Department of Transportation'
15 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
16 'Preamble. Whereas, the Maine Turnpike is the State's most important
17 transportation connection to the rest of the United States; and
18 Whereas, the State has forgone hundreds of millions of dollars in federal funding for
19 Interstate 95 from Kittery to Augusta, as this highway is not eligible for federal subsidy;
20 and
21 Whereas, other states have saved significant resources by eliminating quasi-
22 governmental turnpike authorities with redundant and duplicative staffs, infrastructure and
23 services; and
24 Whereas, the Maine Turnpike Authority has suffered from waste, fraud and abuse of
25 its bonding and spending authority, the costs of which are borne by residents of this State
26 via toll collections by the Maine Turnpike Authority; and
27 Whereas, the tolls on the Maine Turnpike have been raised to pay for unnecessary
28 spending projects when other, higher priority projects elsewhere in the State have been
29 unfunded and Highway Fund revenues have fallen significantly; and
30 Whereas, this resolve establishes a working group to oversee a study of the costs and
31 benefits of and to create a plan for the integration of the Maine Turnpike Authority within
32 the Department of Transportation; now, therefore, be it
33 Sec. 1. Working group established. Resolved: That the Working Group on the
34 Reorganization of the Maine Turnpike Authority, referred to in this resolve as "the working
Page 1 - 132LR1915(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 522, L.D. 1292
315 group," is established to create a plan for the integration of the Maine Turnpike Authority
326 within the Department of Transportation.
3 Sec. 2. Working group membership. Resolved: That, notwithstanding Joint
4 Rule 353, the working group consists of 9 members as follows:
5 1. One member of the Senate, appointed by the President of the Senate;
6 2. One member of the House of Representatives, appointed by the Speaker of the
7 House;
8 3. One member of the public, appointed by the President of the Senate;
9 4. One member of the public, appointed by the Speaker of the House;
10 5. One member with bond counsel experience, appointed by the Treasurer of State;
11 6. Two members of the public with multimodal transportation expertise, appointed
12 jointly by the chairs of the Joint Standing Committee on Transportation;
13 7. The Commissioner of Transportation; and
14 8. The chair of the board of directors of the Maine Turnpike Authority.
15 Sec. 3. Chairs. Resolved: That the Senate member is the Senate chair and the
16 House of Representatives member is the House chair of the working group.
17 Sec. 4. Appointments; convening of working group. Resolved: That all
18 appointments must be made no later than 30 days following the effective date of this
19 resolve. The appointing authorities shall notify the Executive Director of the Legislative
20 Council once all appointments have been completed. After appointment of all members,
21 the chairs shall call and convene the first meeting of the working group. If 30 days or more
22 after the effective date of this resolve a majority of but not all appointments have been
23 made, the chairs may request authority and the Legislative Council may grant authority for
24 the working group to meet and conduct its business.
25 Sec. 5. Examination. Resolved: That the working group shall examine:
26 1. Information on federal funding forgone due to the Maine Turnpike's ineligibility for
27 federal subsidy;
28 2. Estimates of the cost savings from eliminating redundant positions and functions and
29 wasteful spending on inefficient and duplicative efforts and projects by the parallel and
30 overlapping functions of the Maine Turnpike Authority and the Department of
31 Transportation;
32 3. Information on models for management of toll highway systems without a quasi-
33 governmental turnpike authority, such as those in New Hampshire and Massachusetts and
34 elsewhere; and
35 4. Models and options for reallocating toll revenues above what is required for debt
36 service, as well as maintenance of the Maine Turnpike at a standard similar to other limited-
37 access highways in this State.
38 Sec. 6. Plan. Resolved: That, based on the information collected pursuant to
39 section 5, the working group shall create a plan for the integration of the Maine Turnpike
Page 2 - 132LR1915(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 522, L.D. 1292
410 Authority within the Department of Transportation, referred to in this resolve as "the plan,"
421 which must:
3 1. Keep the legal structures, board of directors and toll collection and payments
4 functions of the Maine Turnpike Authority in place only to complete its bond repayment
5 obligations and provide a target date to complete those payments;
6 2. Include a strategy to integrate the staff and decision-making, safety, maintenance
7 and other essential operational functions of the Maine Turnpike Authority into the
8 Department of Transportation over a period of one year from adoption of the plan;
9 3. Assess the costs and benefits associated with the plan; and
10 4. Include draft language for statutory changes to implement the plan.
11 Sec. 7. Staff assistance. Resolved: That the Maine Turnpike Authority and the
12 Department of Transportation shall provide necessary staffing services to the working
13 group.
14 Sec. 8. Report. Resolved: That, no later than January 31, 2026, the working group
15 shall submit a report that includes the plan and suggested legislation to the Office of the
16 Governor, the Joint Standing Committee on Transportation and the Joint Standing
17 Committee on Appropriations and Financial Affairs. The Joint Standing Committee on
18 Transportation may report out legislation based on the report to the Second Regular Session
19 of the 132nd Legislature.
20 Sec. 9. Appropriations and allocations. Resolved: That the following
21 appropriations and allocations are made.
22 TRANSPORTATION, DEPARTMENT OF
23 Highway and Bridge Capital 0406
24 Initiative: Provides one-time funding for an investment grade review and consulting fees
25 to perform the review.
